member.name: T:Microsoft.Azure.Graphs.GremlinGroovy.Binding.GroovyToCsharpGremlinTransformer
member.summary:
Transforms parts of the tree which are groovy-gremlin to csharp-gremlin. This involves visiting groovy AST, identifying gremlin expressions and building a C# LINQ expression tree equivalent. C# LINQ expression tree require binding to C# types/members and as a consequence this uses reflection to find appropriate members to bind to.
DEVNOTE: Was designed to handle groovy-gremlin expressions only, but isn't restricted to this subset alone, and could be expanded to handle any groovy -> C# translation.

member.name: P:Microsoft.Azure.Graphs.GremlinGroovy.Binding.MethodProjection.Rank
member.summary:
Gets a value indicating the rank of the method projection, where the lower the value the less conversions are required to bind the incoming arguments to the target arguments.
Example: Suppose method 'Foo' has overloads: void Foo(object bar) and void Foo(string bar) If the incoming argument is of type string then we would want to choose the second overload over the first. Since the first overload requires object which is not an equivalent to type string, it scores higher resulting in the second overload being chosen.

member.name: P:Microsoft.Azure.Graphs.GraphConnection.VertexPartitionProperty
member.summary:
The vertex property by which the graph is logically partitioned. This distinguishes from partitionFullPath in that the latter is the physical partition key of a document collection.
(1) When partitionFullPath is /_partition, the value of this property is provided by the vertex property VertexPartitionProperty. For example, with VertexPartitionProperty being "id", the graph is logically partitioned by vertex Id, while documents are physically partitioned by /_partition.
(2) In the other cases, VertexPartitionProperty and PartitionFullPath are the same.

member.name: T:Microsoft.Azure.Graphs.Runtime.Enums.JsonDataType
member.summary:
This is a data type enumeration defined for JSON documents. These types are not a JSON standard, but a convention used Json.NET.
Note: the precedence follows that of SQL Server.

Item1: current node. A query will be sent to the server to fetch this node if this is the first time it appears in the whole list. Item2: the traversal edge whose sink is the current node. Item3: traversal edges whose sources are the current node. This list will contain either 0 or 1 traversal edge in the current version, and it will be pushed to server if possible. Item4: backward matching edges. Item5: forward matching edges.

member.name: T:Microsoft.Azure.Graphs.Runtime.Operators.TraversalOperator
member.summary:
The operator that takes a list of records as source vertexes and traverses to their one-hop or multi-hop neighbors. One-hop neighbors are defined in the adjacency lists of the sources. Multi-hop vertices are defined by a recursive function that has a sub-query specifying a single hop from a vertex to another and a boolean fuction controlling when the recursion terminates (in other words, # of hops).
This operators emulates the nested-loop join algorithm.
